# Copy to ONE of: <project>/.env (root), <project>/.jarvis/.env, or ~/.jarvis/.env (global).
# All three are loaded; more specific wins. Fill in and save (ensure it's named ".env",
# not ".env.txt").
# Phase 0 needs NONE of these — the brain uses your Claude subscription via the
# logged-in `claude` CLI. These are for later phases.

# --- Phase 1: voice ---
# Wake word uses openWakeWord ("hey jarvis") by default — no key needed.
# Only the ElevenLabs voice requires keys:
# ELEVENLABS_API_KEY=
# Premade British male voices that work on the FREE plan via API:
#   Daniel (steady broadcaster) onwK4e9ZLuTAKqWW03F9   |   George (warm) JBFqnCBsd6RMkjVDRZzb
# (Voice-Library / community voices like "David" need a PAID ElevenLabs plan to use via API.)
# JARVIS_ELEVENLABS_VOICE_ID=onwK4e9ZLuTAKqWW03F9
#
# Optional: to use the single-word "jarvis" wake engine instead, set
# wake_engine = "porcupine" in .jarvis/config.toml and provide:
# PICOVOICE_ACCESS_KEY=              # free from console.picovoice.ai

# --- Phase 3: Telegram presence ---
# TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=                # from @BotFather
# JARVIS_TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID=          # your chat id

# IMPORTANT: do NOT set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY here — if present it would shadow your
# subscription and bill the API instead. Jarvis unsets it at startup just in case.
